00710 /**
00711  * cvmx_pow_ecc_err
00712  *
00713  * Contains the single and double error bits and the corresponding interrupt enables for the ECC-
00714  * protected POW index memory.  Also contains the syndrome value in the event of an ECC error.
00715  * Also contains the remote pointer error bit and interrupt enable.  RPE is set when the POW
00716  * detected
00717  * corruption on one or more of the input queue lists in L2/DRAM (POW's local copy of the tail
00718  * pointer
00719  * for the L2/DRAM input queue did not match the last entry on the the list).   This is caused by
00720  * L2/DRAM corruption, and is generally a fatal error because it likely caused POW to load bad
00721  * work
00722  * queue entries.
00723  * This register also contains the illegal operation error bits and the corresponding interrupt
00724  * enables as follows:
00725  *  <0> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP from PP in NULL_NULL state
00726  *  <1> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP from PP in NULL state
00727  *  <2> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/GET_WORK from PP with pending tag switch to ORDERED
00728  * or ATOMIC
00729  *  <3> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH from PP with tag specified as NULL_NULL
00730  *  <4> Received SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH from PP with tag specified as NULL
00731  *  <5> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP/GET_WORK/NULL_RD from PP with
00732  * GET_WORK pending
00733  *  <6> Received SWTAG/SWTAG_FULL/SWTAG_DESCH/DESCH/UPD_WQP/GET_WORK/NULL_RD from PP with NULL_RD

01059 /**
01060  * cvmx_pow_nw_tim
01061  *
01062  * Sets the minimum period for a new work request timeout.  Period is specified in n-1 notation
01063  * where the increment value is 1024 clock cycles.  Thus, a value of 0x0 in this register
01064  * translates
01065  * to 1024 cycles, 0x1 translates to 2048 cycles, 0x2 translates to 3072 cycles, etc...  Note:
01066  * the
01067  * maximum period for a new work request timeout is 2 times the minimum period.  Note: the new
01068  * work
01069  * request timeout counter is reset when this register is written.
01070  * There are two new work request timeout cases:
01071  * - WAIT bit clear.  The new work request can timeout if the timer expires before the pre-fetch
01072  *   engine has reached the end of all work queues.  This can occur if the executable work queue
01073  *   entry is deep in the queue and the pre-fetch engine is subject to many resets (i.e. high
01074  * switch,
01075  *   de-schedule, or new work load from other PP's).  Thus, it is possible for a PP to receive a
01076  * work
01077  *   response with the NO_WORK bit set even though there was at least one executable entry in the
01078  *   work queues.  The other (and typical) scenario for receiving a NO_WORK response with the
01079  * WAIT
01080  *   bit clear is that the pre-fetch engine has reached the end of all work queues without
01081  * finding
01082  *   executable work.
01083  * - WAIT bit set.  The new work request can timeout if the timer expires before the pre-fetch
01084  *   engine has found executable work.  In this case, the only scenario where the PP will receive
01085  * a
01086  *   work response with the NO_WORK bit set is if the timer expires.  Note: it is still possible
01087  * for
01088  *   a PP to receive a NO_WORK response even though there was at least one executable entry in
01089  * the
01090  *   work queues.
01091  * In either case, it's important to note that switches and de-schedules are higher priority
01092  * operations that can cause the pre-fetch engine to reset.  Thus in a system with many switches
01093  * or
01094  * de-schedules occuring, it's possible for the new work timer to expire (resulting in NO_WORK
01095  * responses) before the pre-fetch engine is able to get very deep into the work queues.
01096  */

01098     uint64_t u64;
01099     struct cvmx_pow_nw_tim_s {
01100 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01101     uint64_t reserved_10_63               : 54;
01102     uint64_t nw_tim                       : 10; /**< New work timer period */
01103 #else
01104     uint64_t nw_tim                       : 10;
01105     uint64_t reserved_10_63               : 54;
01106 #endif
01107     } s;
